< Text>
Unfortunately, Mammoth does not have a lot of higher-end restaurants but Petra is definitely a solid option for foodies.

Service is very good and the food is well priced given the quality.

Order the Baked Brie or the Duck Confit as an appetizer...Salmon or Short Ribs for Main Course.

ENJOY!< /Text>

<text>The food was really delicious (you can expect the same food quality as in a French restaurant) and worth the price (which is reasonably high).
The wine is a bit overpriced but their wine list is huge and you can find anything from all over the world.
The service was acceptable until the moment they bring the bill: they announce a 18%gratuity fee for groups of 6 people or more but it seems that our waitress  decided to add it to our bill  even if we were only 2 sitting at our table and their only explanation to that is that they use to do that with tourists to make sure they get a decent tip!
So in case you're a tourist like we were (and like the 90% of customers they should have) you can expect to be charged with the "tourist fee"!< /text><pictures>None< /pictures>< Response>

< Text>
Friendly staff and a clean facility. Im used to going to 24 hour fitness or golds gym .10dollars a month.Dumbbells go up to 75lbs. A variety of machines including  the smith machines (I know) tredmils and sit up benches. No barbell bench, squat rack or dead lift barbells which will lead me to going to another gym. Planet fitness isn't for seasoned body builders for sure because their just isn't enough weight to lift. But if your a beginner, short on cash, just tryna do cardio, not tryna become a beast than planet fitness is for you. Some people here are actually tryna make gains.At the end of the day you can do what ever you wanna do!</Text>

< Text>
If you havent already, get to this peak. It's a challenge, but the views are your reward. Bring water and of it's too hot, please don't subject your dog to such conditions. Dogs have died here due to heat stroke. I implore you avoid it. However, there are plenty of pet-friendly trails that will keep you and your furry companion happy and safe.</Text>

< user_id>
105262460060530761289</user_id>
<name>Marcus Castle</name>< date>
1551189698376< /date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
I have an affinity and love for Mission Trails. The trails are well cared for, and you couldn't ask for a more accessible location. It's impressive how this natural park can be situated smack in a central location to just about anywhere in San Diego, yet maintain its natural beauty and feeling of isolation. Kwaay Paay mountain is central to the park, but the trail heads (there are two) are only found on the east side of the park. Being just over a mile oh, it's a super short trail. It starts out as more of a rolling, gentle climb, and gets a little more intense near the end. As you close in on the peak, there are a few areas that are going to require some rock scrambling, although it's nothing that can't be handled easily with a trekking pole. Have fun!<//text>

<date>1520808017131<//date><Rate>5</Rate><Review>Trail is marked "difficult" or 3 out of 3. People of all ages and physical shapes made it to the top - but I wouldn't say this trail was easy! Take your time, if needed, but there not no benches to take stops and the trail gets very narrow with tree brush throughout the hike. Also remember your water! I didn't notice any water or trash stations on this specific trail. The peak is really pretty though with a 360 view and there are dozens of large rocks to use as a seat once you're to the very top. Thank you for your business.'}</resp><date>1600266762360<//date><user>109888580663185407027</user><review>After recently purchasing a house, we needed to have some minor electrical corrected, and several fans/control switches/can lights/dimmer switches and a stand-alone RV power outlet installed. We heard about Raceway through our realtor (who had used them for a number of years for their own properties). On the day of installation, Billy and Sam arrived on time, and were very professional and personable. Billy took our requests/needs into account for the install, and suggested very logical options that would work for the room size. We went with Billy's recommendations, and everything turned out excellent! They both worked very efficiently and answered any questions we had along the way.
Thank you guys!

A few weeks after the install, we noticed one of the fans (Brand: Minka Aire)  was making a ticking noise while operating at higher speeds. Raceway sent Sam to take a look. He figured out the problem in a few minutes, and made the correction (putting two 2" sections of gasket material 180deg apart between the ceiling and the base cover). No more ticking!!
Per the fan retailer and Raceway, this is a common issue with this brand of fans.

We intend to use Raceway for future projects.
Highly recommended!< /review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< gmapID>

I bought a Digitech iPB10 from them on ebay.  It works fine!  The listing stated that it was missing two rubber pads on the foot pedal, but I bought it anyway.  What was also missing, but not stated in the listing were the following:  1) the original box; 2) the original power supply (a Line 6 one was substituted and works fine); 3) the product manual; and 4) the rubber insert that enables the unit to be used with a thinner, second generation iPad. < user_id>
115687222522362685364<//user_id>
<Name>MACTackleBox<//Name><Date>1528431175857<//Date><Rate>3<//Rate>< Text>
This is a Fabulous location!! We ate outside with the Capitol in the background. The sun was setting and the patio was draped in twinkle lights. You will not find a better view downtown, Anywhere! 5 stars for ambiance/location. The waiter we had was lovely! 5 stars for him, too. I really wanted to love the duck but it was Well Done instead of Medium. The cherry demi glace seemed to be more like melted Cherry Jam. In their defense, I know it takes some time to work out the kinks when opening a new restaurant. Our waiter made sure we were taken care of when all was said and done. (I told you he was good!) We'll give them some time to become a well-oiled machine before we go back.<//Text>

<user>105910087207786692149</user>< date>
1548032357625</date>
<rate>4</rate>< Text>
We like to try restaurants that are new to us, so on Saturday night before the Philharmonic concert my husband and I took advantage of the special $35 per person Dine Downtown menu. The decor is beautiful, elegant, & soothing.  We spent $40 on 4 glasses of a Rhone blend red wine that we enjoyed. The service and food were all good, but the portions were comically tiny. While the starter salads were of normal size, my salmon entree was 3 ounces at most.  His bacon wrapped filet couldn't have been more than 4 ounces and was accompanied by 2 potatoes the size of grape tomatoes.  The dessert eclairs were the size of my pinky finger.  Their regular menu is much higher priced, so I would hope those portions would be larger as well.</Text>

< review>
It was Dine Downtown and nice restaurants put their best foot forward for $35 for a 3 course dinner. We were seated and their was an extra napkin under the table. I ordered the Lobster Bisque, Bacon wrapped filet, and eclair for dessert. The Lobster Bisque tasted like tomato soup and drawn butter, not lobster bisque. The bacon wrapped filet was stuffed wit a spear of asparagus and wrapped with bacon. It was the size of my thumb. The meat was tough and the three marble sized potatoes that came with it tasted best. Dessert was half of what appeared to be a stale leclair. I cant speak well of the service as well. The male waiter could use deoderant. Overall, one of the worst meals I have ever had.< /review>

<Date>1571873178532< /Date>< user_name>

<user_id>109847641087234565022</user_id>< pics>

< gmap_id>

<gmap_id>0x54cd0104c51fec61:0x7e75ce39a3b779c1< /gmap_id>< time>
1475017838532</time>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>
< Review>
Out exploring the mountains around Mt Shasta and got hungry.   Stopped into Ortega's based on lack of options and good reviews.  As many Mexican restaurants go this is a family run business.   It is small and cozy and the servers are friendly and polite. Chips and salsa were very good,  with the chips being light and crispy.   Tried the Chicken chimichanga based on others reviews and found it to be good.... not great but good.

The amazing dish was the fried ice  cream.... I have tried many and most taste stale like they were made yesterday.    This was fresh and crispy like it was made to order.... I highly recommend it!  A single scoop of vanilla ice cream covered in something like crushed corn flakes then deep fried.   This is then put into a fried flour tortilla "bowl"  and the whole concoction is sprinkled with sugar and cinnamon with a dollop of whipped cream on top and drizzled with chocolate syrup!<//Review>

My first visit here.  I love lamb, and the server suggested a dish of 2 lamb chops, 2 chicken and 1 beef kabob, and a dinner salad.  The price above the dinner she suggested was $19.50.  For me, that's a very expensive lunch, but it sounded special.  It was good.  When the tab came, it was $34.50!  I wouldn't spend that much for a good dinner!  When I questioned it, she said that selection she described wasn't the $19.50 selection, but a selection further up the menu.  As I said, I would never have spent $34.50 on lunch no matter how good it sounded.  It may have been an honest mistake, but for someone not familiar with the menu, I think some kind of discount should have been offered.<//review>

< review>
I just had dinner with my husband and two couples of friends in Aladdin, and went through a horrible experience. I visited the restaurant many times before, since the food is good. But after what I went through today, I will never return to the place. We ordered a descent amount of food, which was all good. But then the waitress mistakenly brought out two portions of Mawashi, (despite the fact that we ordered only one) and the meat in it was raw. We immediately requested to return the dish, and then a young kid named Ali said the chef checked the Mawashi and the meat is fine. Therefore he'll charge us for one of the portions that we ordered, since we ordered only one portion and not two. We asked to speak with the manager, and Ali said that he already left. When we asked our waitress Sandra to call the manager, she said we just spoke to one... Surprisingly Ali happens to be the owner's son who's apparently ruining his dad's business by providing an awful customer service. If one of your loyal customers requests to return a dish you don't confront him and try to prove him wrong! You should simply apologize and give him a refund. Not one minute passed by and Sandra approached our table again asking if we'd like to order desert and offered boxes to go. We said we're good, but then she said that since this is a dangerous neighborhood the restaurant requests its customers to leave by 9pm, and handed us the bill. We told her we live down the street and we find it offensive that she considers Clairmont as a dangerous neighborhood. She replied "l know, me too". The restaurant was still filled with people. What a rude attempt to kick out your customers. When reviewing the bill we saw that not only they added the raw Mawashi as Ali said he would, but also added 18% gratuity charge to the bill. I happened to eat in many restaurants around the world, and never have I felt so unwanted and disrespected.</review>

<user_id>113266336642580442511< /user_id><Text>Aladdin's definitely has the market cornered on Mediterranean food in San Diego. It's often a favorite for a Sunday lunch with my family.

While the location is convenient to the 805 freeway, the parking can be a hassle. It shares the parking lot with other businesses, and while it looks large, it's surprisingly small. The restaurant is super casual, but it feels nice and open. It's always clean, and inviting.

You can't beat the food there. We usually get the Meza Platter - a dish that comes with 8 small dishes that includes hummus, babaganoush, chicken, lamb, and a bunch of other things, along with a pizza. The baklava is great too. Served with ice cream. These three things fed 5 hungry adults. Service is standard and prices are very reasonable.

This place could easily host large parties and kids are always welcomed there.

I always look forward to going to Aladdin's.<//Text>< Rating>
5<//Rating>

<text>Aladdin's definitely has the market cornered on Mediterranean food in San Diego. It's often a favorite for a Sunday lunch with my family.

While the location is convenient to the 805 freeway, the parking can be a hassle. It shares the parking lot with other businesses, and while it looks large, it's surprisingly small. The restaurant is super casual, but it feels nice and open. It's always clean, and inviting.

You can't beat the food there. We usually get the Meza Platter - a dish that comes with 8 small dishes that includes hummus, babaganoush, chicken, lamb, and a bunch of other things, along with a pizza. The baklava is great too. Served with ice cream. These three things fed 5 hungry adults. Service is standard and prices are very reasonable.

This place could easily host large parties and kids are always welcomed there.

I always look forward to going to Aladdin's.<//text>< Pics>

<Time>1579988743841</Time><text>I don't know where to begin. My wife ordered the lentil soup. It was pureed. I've never had pureed lentils at a Mediterranean restaurant. Maybe I've been eating at inauthentic restaurants or maybe this was just not prepared in the traditional manner. I ordered a chicken shawarma sandwich. It was not only greasy, dripping with brown oil, but covered in some indescribable sauce - one I've never had in 53 years of eating Mediterranean food. There were no tomatoes, lettuce or any type of yogurt-based sauce that I've always seen served with shawarma. Again, maybe I've had inauthentic food. Finally, the dolma were the type that have been marinated in tomato sauce. I prefer them without sauce, so this is a preference issue rather than one of authenticity. Regardless, they were not my favorite. Ultimately, this was not a good experience for us, and I don't intend to return.</text><Name>David Miller<//Name>< UserId.>

<user>101520184619030112062<//user>< username>
Tricia Pooladi<//username>
<date>1551755325411< /date>< Rate>
3<//Rate>
< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
< Text>
Cute atmosphere, wide selection of herbal teas and Mediterranean foods. They have hookah, so I think it's a hookah bar at night. The falafel appetizer was really delicious. I wish they served it Amsterdam Falafel style (WDC friends know what I'm talking about). Comes with pita triangles and tahini. I ordered a Greek salad, and the Greek salad was very good - I made little falafel pitas with the salad.
Mylo got the Fatoush salad, and it looked a little lacking - seemed to be light on the s'mac but they were really skimpy on the pita chips and didn't have feta on it although you can add it. Salad itself was large. Dave got the lamb schwarma and he said it was good. It came with a nice little greek salad, but I will have to try the schwarma for myself -- looked like it might be dry. Turkish coffee is delicious. Has a bit of minty flavor, which was quite pleasant.

Meal menu is a bit overpriced, service can be slow.< /Text>
